article.headline: UCLA 64, Washington 59
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- With last season's blowout loss on their minds,
the UCLA Bruins focused on defense Thursday night against the
Washington Huskies -- and came up with a 64-59 victory.

Noelle Quinn scored 25 points and had 11 rebounds for the
winners.

The Bruins' Lisa Willis tied the contest at 54 when she made a
3-pointer and made her foul shot after being fouled by the Huskies'
Nicole Castro with less than three minutes to play. On the very
next possession, Jamila Veasley scored running down the lane to
give the Bruins (11-10, 6-6 Pac-10) the lead for good.

"I remember looking at the clock with less than three minutes
to play and Nikki (Blue) saying there is a lot of game left,"
Quinn said.

Last season, the Bruins lost here 111-77 as the Huskies hit
their first six 3-pointers en route to an easy win. This year, UCLA
came with a different look.

"We talked about coming out strong and not letting them get a
big lead," Bruins head coach Kathy Olivier said. "Our goal was to
get a hand in their face and play tight defense."

Giuliana Mendiola scored a game-high 27 points for Washington
(12-9, 5-7). Mendiola added five assists, tying her for the
Huskies' school record with Leteia Hughley (1982-85) with 559.

"I thought we were getting a lot of momentum in that stretch
(late in the game), but we had a lot of mental breakdowns,"
Mendiola said. "We can't be having those this late in the
season."

Andrea Lalum had nine points for the Huskies.

"I thought we showed some maturity tonight," Olivier said.

Willis finished with 13 points and Blue added 11 for UCLA.

Mendiola's fade-away jumper with less than two seconds left in
the first half gave the Huskies a 24-23 halftime lead.
